[1] Case Update

May 29, 2018. Epidemiological Situation. Democratic Republic of Congo, Ministry of Health
https://us13.campaign-archive.com/home/?u=89e5755d2cca4840b1af93176&id=aedd23c530 [in French, machine trans., edited]

The Epidemiological Situation of Ebola Virus Disease, 28 May 2018:
- A total of 51 cases of haemorrhagic fever were reported in the region, including 35 confirmed, 13 probable and 3 suspected.
- 2 new suspected cases: 1 in Iboko, 1 in Wangata
- 5 negative tests: 4 in Iboko, 1 in Wangata
- No new positive case
- No new deaths

Epidemiological analyzes have identified contacts living in nearby health areas in Bikoro and Iboko. These contacts are followed and advised to limit their movements during the entire follow-up period of 21 days.

News from the Ebola response

Searching for the latest suspicious cases and contacts in Bongonzo district (Mbandaka)
- After his last trip to Mbandaka, the Minister of Health, Dr. Oly Ilunga Kalenga, instructed the provincial response coordination teams to conduct a search in the Bongonzo district of Mbandaka town in order to identify the latest suspicious cases and contacts. It was in the Bongonzo neighborhood that the patients who had left the Wangata Ebola Treatment Center had taken refuge.
- In the coming days, experts in epidemiological surveillance will move from household to household to ensure that all people who have been in contact with patients are followed and benefit from vaccination. They will be accompanied by teams in charge of communication and psycho-social monitoring to raise awareness among households.

Strengthening activities in Itipo
- During his last visit to Itipo, the Minister of Health was informed that the local population complained that their sick relatives had to be treated in the nearby health area of Bikoro. So far, patients are temporarily taken care of in a transit center in Itipo before being transferred to the Bikoro Reference General Hospital, thus finding themselves far from their families.
- As a result, the Ministry of Health has asked Ministry of Health teams and partners to strengthen all components of the Ebola response in Itipo. A mobile laboratory has already been delivered; community-based surveillance activities will be strengthened, and an Ebola treatment center will soon be installed.

******
[2] Past Lessons

28 May 2018. Aid workers heed past lessons as they battle Congo Ebola outbreak
[FT, edited] https://www.ft.com/content/2ac3f40c-5ffe-11e8-9334-2218e7146b04 [Byline: John Aglionby]

Rapid roll out of protection kits and traveller screening

Aid workers were just finishing a briefing for local health workers in Mbandaka, the city that is at the centre of an Ebola outbreak, when an emergency call came in. "Someone said: 'Quick there's a suspect patient in this place, you need to go and pick them up'," said Henry Gray, Médecins Sans Frontières coordinator in the Congolese city of one million people. "When they got back, there was another call. There had been a death in the community, and we had to do a safe burial."

It is an example of how aid agencies and Congolese health officials have been working 18 hours a day in Mbandaka to contain an outbreak of the deadly virus since the 1st case was reported in the city 400 km northeast of the capital Kinshasa 11 days ago. The aim is to prevent a repeat of the devastating 2014-16 outbreak in west Africa that killed 11 600, when a slow and poorly coordinated response was blamed for prolonging the crisis.

There have been 56 reported infections and 25 deaths since the 1st case in the latest outbreak in the Democratic Republic of Congo was confirmed in the remote Bikoro region on 8 May 2018, according to the health ministry. "It's somewhere between on a knife-edge and under control," said Michael Ryan, an assistant director-general of the World Health Organisation who is coordinating the UN response to the crisis. "Things are improving, but I don't believe we've yet detected every possible case, so we are remaining at very high alert.

"We're dealing with extremes here, a densely populated city at one end, to a deep forest situation at the other." Health workers in Mbandaka say myriad lessons have been learned from the West Africa epidemic, where Mr Gray said the response was "clearly not adequate".

"The response has been a lot stronger with a lot more resources brought to bear," said the veteran of 9 such crises. "It hasn't made the difference yet, but when we look back in hindsight, it will be noted that this early stage and massive mobilisation of resources ... will have helped."

International experts said a big difference had been that the host government had made no attempt to downplay the risks of the virus spreading. They added that Kinshasa had shown strong leadership despite the government being embroiled in a long-running political crisis over the refusal of President Joseph Kabila to step down at the end of his elected term.

Protection kits were sent to hospitals in Mbandaka, and traveller screening was started before the confirmation of the 1st cases in the city of the highly contagious virus that is spread by fruit bats.

"The government knew this outbreak presented a higher risk than last year's [2018] [smaller] outbreak due to the fact the health workers were among the 1st victims," said Oly Ilunga, the health minister. "All the major international organisations have worked in better alignment with the government's Ebola response plan."

