[3] Treatment and logistic centers
- MSF Ebola Treatment Center
- WHO logistical base

29 May 2018. With a capacity of 40 beds, the Ebola Treatment Center is ready - photo report
[Actualite.cd] https://actualite.cd/2018/05/29/rdc-mbandaka-avec-une-capacite-de-40-lits-le-centre-de-traitement-debola-est-pret-reportage-photos/

Located 15 km from Mbandaka, the Ebola Treatment Center has been ready since Sunday [27 May 2018] to welcome all cases that were initially intended for the Wangata Reference General Hospital.

This center is built and managed by Médecins Sans Frontières (MSF). With a capacity of 40 beds, this center has anticipated the possibility of an explosion of the epidemic.

"We are planning different phases. The 1st phase provides for about 40 beds in total. It's more ambitious than the number of patients we have today, but we want to be well prepared. We will have about 20 beds for suspected cases and the same number of beds for confirmed cases," Henri Gray, head of MSF's intervention in Mbandaka, told Actualite.cd.

The site belongs to the Catholic Church, which donated it for medical care. It can accommodate up to 50 people and MSF staff. The work had attracted locals who, for the most part, were happy with the facility.

27 May 2018. Mbandaka: David Gressly hails "quick mobilization" against Ebola fever
[Radio Okapi, edited] https://www.radiookapi.net/2018/05/27/actualite/sante/mbandaka-david-gressly-salue-la-mobilisation-rapide-contre-la-fievre

The response to the outbreak of Ebola haemorrhagic fever in Mbandaka and Bikoro "is encouraging," the UN Deputy Special Representative in the DRC in charge of operations, David Gressly, said on Saturday [26 May 2018]. For 2 days, he visited the coordination activities in Mbandaka and the field response in Iboko, about 180 km southeast of Mbandaka.

MONUSCO must not deviate from its logistical support mission for the well-being and security of the Congolese, according to David Gressly. This is why, as a result of this epidemic of Ebola haemorrhagic fever in Mbandaka and Bikoro, the UN mission immediately undertook several actions, at the request of the Congolese authorities.

The 1st is the rehabilitation of the emergency operation center, which is the headquarters of the provincial coordination in Mbandaka. In this center, MONUSCO proceeds with the repair and equipment of the building, with the establishment of electricity and the Internet connection, in order to facilitate the digitization of the response.

During his 48-hour stay in Equateur, David Gressly also visited the site that houses the logistics base for managing the Ebola crisis. It is being renovated by MONUSCO at Mbandaka airport.

This base will be used by all partners in support of the response. Added to this is a camp of medical personnel that MONUSCO built in Iboko, where several new suspected cases have just been reported. The goal is to counter the spread of the epidemic beyond this border community to the province of Mai-Ndombe.

But, David Gressly rather completed his mission on Saturday [26 May 2018] with a note of satisfaction of the work carried out and the collaboration between partners engaged in the response: "The mobilization for the response to this epidemic is impressive. So, I'm very happy to see that under the leadership of the government and WHO, I believe that with this rapid mobilization we can finally contain this epidemic."

